.TH LSIOMMU 1 "July 2026" "Linux System Utilities" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
lsiommu \- Enumerate IOMMU groups, and list the PCIe devices and USB
controllers associated with each group
.SH DESCRIPTION
lsiommu is a hardware inspection utility that shows the relationships between
IOMMU groups, physical PCIe hardware, and nested USB buses.
.PP
It is commonly used when setting up Kernel-based Virtual Machines (KVM) with
VFIO hardware passthrough (i.e., PCIe passthrough of a host device, such as a
graphics card or a network interface, to a guest VM).
.PP
The utility performs four core actions:
.TP
.BR "Group Mapping"
Iterates sequentially through the system kernel directory
.I /sys/kernel/iommu_groups/
to discover physical hardware isolation clusters.
.TP
.BR "Hardware Details"
Executes
.BR lspci (8)
queries to extract and cleanly format vendor names, hardware descriptions, and
precise hardware IDs for graphics cards, network interfaces, and storage
drives.
.TP
.BR "Reset Support Flag"
Checks the system tree for device reset capabilities.
It appends an
.B [R]
flag if a hardware device natively supports a function-level reset, which is
required for reliable virtual machine attach/detach cycles.
.TP
.BR "USB Mapping"
Correlates nested USB controllers via
.BR lsusb (8)
with their parent PCIe buses.  This exposes exactly which physical USB ports
belong to which isolated IOMMU group.
.SH NOTES
IOMMU groups are a part of the kernel's VFIO (Virtual Function IO) driver
framework:
.TP
.BR https://docs.kernel.org/driver-api/vfio.html
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR lspci (8),
.BR lsusb (8),
